gical approaches, including literary analysis and history, linguistics, ethics, and queer, cultural, and film studies, Sanchez sheds new light on texts by T.S. Eliot, Ezra Pound, Gertrude Stein, William Carlos Williams, Charlie Chaplin, and many others. By approaching modernism through the perspective of Deaf and disability studies, Deafening Modernism reconceptualizes deafness as a critical modality enabling us to freshly engage topics we thought we knew.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9781479847501.001.0001zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479847501zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781479847501/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA